The Global Existance of Solutions to the Microscopic Model

Symbols and Definitions

  1. G(V,E) is a graph with vertex set V and edge set E.
  2. The adjacency matrix of E is denoted by A=(aij)n×n, where n:=|V|.
  3. The neighbour of node/vertex i∈V is defined as N(i):={j:j∼i}.
  4. The conductivity and length of edge i→j are denoted by Cij and Lij correspondingly, where Cij≥0 and Lij>0.
  5. The pressure of the vertex i∈V is denoted by Pi. Thus we can define the pressure drop (ΔP)ij:=Pj−Pi by definition.
  6. The flow rate of an oriented flux in i→j is denoted by Qij:=Cij(ΔP)ijLij.
  7. The strength of i, denoted by Si, is defined as the negative summation of Qij for all j∈N(i).
  8. Hk(Ω):=Wk,2(Ω) is a kind of Соболев space, that is, the subset of functions f in L2(Ω) such that f and its weak derivatives up to order k have a finite L2 norm.
  9. H01(Ω) is a subset of functions g in H1(Ω) such that g has a compact support on Ω.

Formulae

  1. Kirchhoff's first law is that the algebraic sum of currents in a network of conductors meeting at a point (or node) is zero. Thus

    Si=∑j∈N(i)Cij(ΔP)jiLij=−∑j∈N(i)Cij(ΔP)ijLij

  2. The global mass conservation reveals that

    ∑i∈VSi=0

  3. The Joule’s law illustrates that the kinetic energy is in proportion to both pressure drop and flow rate. Thus

    E1[Cij]:=(ΔP)ijQij=Qij2CijLij

  4. The metabolic consumption (in energy form) is in proportion to its length and a power of its conductivity. Thus

    E2[Cij]:=νγCijγLij

  5. The entire energy consumption functional is given by

    E~[C]:=∑(i,j)∈E(Qij2Cij+νγCijγ)Lij

Analysis of Discrete Model

The gradient of energy consumption functional w.r.t. Cij.

We notice that Q=Q[C], while ν and Lij is independent from Cij. The partial derivetive of E~[C]

∂∂CijE~[C]:=∂∂Cij∑(i,j)∈E(Qij2Cij+νγCijγ)Lij:=νCijγ−1Lij−Qij2Cij2Lij+2∑(i,j)∈EQijCij∂Qij∂CijLij

We notice that Si are fixed constants. Hence

2∑(i,j)∈EQijCij∂Qij∂CklLij=∑i=1n∑j=1naij(Pj−PiLij∂Qij∂Ckl)Lij=∑j=1nPj∑i=1naij∂Qij∂Ckl−∑i=1nPi∑j=1naij∂Qij∂Ckl=−2∑i=1nPi∑j=1naij∂Qij∂Ckl=−2∑i=1nPi∂∂Ckl∑j∈N(i)Qij=−2∑i=1nPi∂∂CklSi=0

Thus we deduce the gradient

∇E~[C]=(⋯,νCijγ−1Lij−Qij2Cij2Lij,⋯)

The gradient descent flow

In general case, the gradient flow is introduced to find the decreasing streamline. Let f:Rn→R be a differentiable function with a given initial point (x0,f(x0)). There exists a streamline η(x,t) such that η(x,t)=f∘x(t) descends when t is increasing.

The general formulation of a gradient flow of the functional E~∘C(t) is of the form

dCdt=−H[C]⋅∇E~[C]

We denote the space of tanent and cotangent vectors at C∈C by TCC andTC∗C respectively. Therefore H[C] can be regarded as a duality map

H[C]:TC∗C→TCC

For any positive difinite duality map H[C], we have

dE~[C]dt=∇E~[C]⋅dCdt=⟨∇E~[C],∇E~[C]⟩H[C]<0

which implies the dissipation of the energy along the solutions to gradient of energy consumption functional coupled with the Kirchhoff law.

The gradient flow of energy function coupled with the Kirchhoff law with respect to the unweighted Euclidean distance is given by the identical map H. Thus

dCdt=−∇E[C]~

Based on this general formulation, we consider the gradient flow with respect to a weighted Euclidean distance and introduce a duality map resulting in the ODE system, given by

H[C]=H1[C]⊗⋯⊗H|E|[C]

Here

Hij[C]:∂Cij|C↦Cijα⋅dCij

Thus

dCijdt=(QijCij2Lij−νCijγLij)Cijα−1

The non-singularity of C~

The global existance of the solutions hinges on the the non-singularity of the Kirchhoff matrix C~′. Consider the matrix C~ such that C~⋅P=S, where

C~⋅P=S⇔(∑j≠1C1jL1j−C12L12⋯−C1nL1n−C21L21∑j≠2C2jL2j⋯−C2nL2n⋮⋱⋱⋮−Cn1Ln1⋯−Cnn−1Lnn−1∑j≠nCnjLnj)(P1P2⋮Pn)=(S1S2⋮Sn)

Given that the all-one vector space is a trivial kernel of C~, we shall consider the array-deleted matrix C′, i.e.

C~′:=(∑j≠2C2jL2j−C23L23⋯−C2nL2n−C32L32∑j≠3C3jL3j⋯−C3nL3n⋮⋱⋱⋮−Cn2Ln2⋯−Cnn−1Lnn−1∑j≠nCnjLnj)

which seems promising to be non-singular.

Theorem. The matrix A is non-singulat if A is weakly diagonally dominant and irreducable.

  • A is reducable iff the graph with respect to A is connected. An equivalnet statement states that there exists a permutation matrix P such that

    P−1AP=PTAP=(A1A2OA3)

  • A weakly diagonally dominant iff there for all diagonal element aii the inequality |aii|≥∑j≠i|aij| holds, among which at least one of the equalities do not hold.

Proof. For contradiction, suppose that detA=0, then dim⁡ker⁡A≥1, i.e. there exists a non zero vector v=(v1,…,vn) such that Av=0. We define Y by

Y:{k:infi|vi|<|vk|=∥v∥∞}

  1. If Y is empty, then |vi|−|vj|≡0. Thus for any k

    |akk||vk|=|∑l≠kaklvl|≤∑l≠k|akl||vl|

    Thus |akk|≤∑l≠k|akl|, which contradicts the weakly diagonally dominance of A.

  2. When Y is non-empty. Notice that

    |akk|≤∑j≠k|akl||vl||vk|

    and

    |akk|≥∑j≠k|akl|

    Thus for all i∈Y and j∉Y, we have aij=0, which contradicts the reducability of A.

The proof is completed and thence we shall shift to the proof of connectivity of C and the non-vanishment of all Cij∈C. The proof of the global existance of solutions to the formulae

dCijdt=(QijCij2Lij−νCijγLij)Cijα−1Lij

is presented below.

The global existance of Cij(t)

We shall proof the global existance of the ODE system

dCijdt=(QijCij2Lij−νCijγLij)Cijα−1Lij

coupled with the Kirchhoff law. Firstly we notice that the graph generated by all non-zero initial datum of Cij(t0) is connected. WLOG assume t0=0, then we shall prove that 0<Cij(t)<Fij(t) on R+, where Fij(t) is a continuous dominance function defined on (0,∞). Here α∈R, γ>0 and γ+α−1>0.

If α+γ≥2, then

dCijdt≥−νLijCijγ+α−1

Since the exponent γ+α−1≥1 and Cij(0)>0, the solution of Cij(t) remains positive for all t>0. Moreover, Cij(t) remains bounded since the dissipation of the energy along the solutions.

If α+γ∈(1,2), then we can divide V in to V1 and V2 such that the sources and sinks induce a net flux between them. We shall prove that the connections between V1 and V2 maintains along the corresponding solutions.

Let E~ be the set of edges connecting V1 and V2. By definition of V1 and V2, we have

ΔS:=∑i∈V1Si=−∑j∈V2Sj≠0

Assume that ∑(i,j)∈E~Cij(t0)>0. We shall prove that

∑(i,j)∈E~Cij(t)>0,∀t>t0

In light of the local existance of the solutions of C, we suppose that there exists T>t0 such that

limt→T−∑(i,j)∈E~Cij(t)=0

for contradiction. Since α−2<0 and γ+α−1>0, for all t∈(t0,T) we have

ddt∑(i,j)∈E~Cij(t)=∑(i,j)∈E~(Qij2Cijα−2−νCijγ+α−1)Lij=∑(i,j)∈E~Qij2Cijα−2Lij−∑(i,j)∈E~νCijγ+α−1Lij≥(∑(i,j)∈E~Cij)α−2∑(i,j)∈E~Qij2Lij−(∑(i,j)∈E~Cij)γ+α−1∑(i,j)∈E~νLij

Since

∑(i,j)∈E~Qij2Lij≥∑(i,j)∈E~Qij2inf(i,j)∈E~Lij≥|ΔS|2|E~|inf(i,j)∈E~Lij

Denote ∑(i,j)∈E~Cij(t) by u(t). We have

1|E~|ddtu(t)≥uα−2(t)⋅|ΔS|2|E~|inf(i,j)∈E~Lij−uγ+α−1(t)∑(i,j)∈E~νLij=defuα−2(t)A+uα+γ−1(t)B

Here A and B are positive constants.

Since the derivation of u(t) remains positive when t is large enough, the minimum of u is min({u(t0)}∪{u(t):u′(t)=0})=min{u(t0),A/Bγ+1}>0, which contradicts the assumption that limt→T−∑(i,j)∈E~Cij(t)=0.

If V can be partitioned into two balanced subgraphs V1 and Vj, then we can continue to deduct separately for each of the subgraphs (until the eventual step).

Via the graph partirioning method above, we deduce the global existence of the solutions.

Analysis of the Macroscopic Model

The energy consumption functional on Rd

For all i∈V, denote the left and right neighbours of vertex i on the k-th spatial dimension (if exist) by (i−1)k and (i−1)k respectively. Thus the Kirchhoff law is then written as

−∑k=1dC(i−1)k,i(ΔP)(i−1)k,iL(i−1)k,i−Ci,(i+1)k(ΔP)i,(i+1)kLi,(i+1)k=Si

When the points in the set V are arranged as a set of parallelotopes or rectangular tessellation, that is, with the equal length hk to the left or right neighbour with respect to the k-th spatial dimension. The Kirchhoff law is written as

−∑k=1dC(i−1)k,i(ΔP)(i−1)k,ihk−Ci,(i+1)k(ΔP)i,(i+1)khk=Si

In the rescaling of the energy functional, some (abstract) weights are applied to scale linearly with the grid spacing, i.e.

E~[C]=∑(i,j)∈E(Qij2Cij+νγCijγ)Wij(d)

Via the deduction of the gradient of energy consumption functional as shown above, we conclude that the formal gradient flow (with respect to the Euclidean distance) of the energy functional constrained by the rescaled Kirchhoff law is of the type, i.e.

dCijdt=(Qij2Cij2+νCijγ−1)Wij(d)

if and only if all the weights Wij(d) are equal. Here one of the natural way to choose Wij(d) is letting Wij(d)≡W(d)=∏k=1dhk(d).

The Discrete Approximation of the Poisson Equation

One can notice that the Kirchhoff law is a finite difference discretization of the Poisson equation per se. Furthermore, the approximation is the Riemann sum of the integral-type funcitonal.

Consider the solution p(x) of the Poisson equation

−∇⋅(c∇p)=S

Here c=diag (c1,c2,⋯,cd) is a diagonal permeabwhility tensor field with scalar non-negative functions ck∈C(Ω). The global mass balance lies that

∫∂ΩS(x)dx=0

We as ssume that the solution p(x) is at least C2 on Ω and c are C1 on Ω. Since c(x)=diag (c1,c2,…,cn) is diagonal, the finite difference approximation of S is

S=−∇⋅(c∇p)=−∑k=1d∂xk(ck∂xkp)=−∑k=1dck(x(i+1/2)k)∂xkp(x(i+1/2)k)−ck(x(i−1/2)k)∂xkp(x(i−1/2)k)hk(d)+O(hk(d))=−∑k=1dck(x(i+1/2)k)⋅p(x(i+1)k)−p(x(i)k)hk(d)−ck(x(i−1/2)k)⋅p(x(i)k)−p(x(i−1)k)hk(d)hk(d)+O(hk(d))=⋯=−∑k=1dC(i−1)k,i(ΔP)(i−1)k,iL(i−1)k,i−Ci,(i+1)k(ΔP)i,(i+1)kLi,(i+1)k+O(hk(d))

When we equal ck(x(i±1/2)k) with Ci,(i±1)k, Si with S(Xi), Pi with p(Xi) and Pi±1 with p(Xi±1), the rescaled Kirchhoff's law is concluded to be the discrete approximation of the Poisson function.

Moreover, we can estimate

∫Ω|ck|γdx=W(d)∑i∈V|ck(X(i+1/2)k)|γ+O(hk(d))

and

∫Ωck(∂xkp)2dx=W(d)∑i∈Vck(X(i+1/2)k)(p(X(i+1)k)−p(Xi)hk(d))2+O(hk(d))

Thus the energy functional with respect to rectangular grid parallelotopes can be written as

E~[C]=12∑k=1d∑i∈V∑j∈N(i;k)(Qij2[C]Cij+νγCijγ)hk(d)

Here N(i;k) denotes N(i)∩{(i±1)k}, that is, the neighbour in the kth spatial dimension.

Via the notation we applied in the discrete approximation, we have

E~[C]+O(W(d))=E[c]=∫Ω∇p⋅c∇p+νγ|c|γdx

Here |c|:=∑k=1d|ck|γ.

The formal L2 -Gradient Flow of the Energy

In retrospect to how we have deducted dCdt, we shall estimate the the formal L2-gradient flow of the continuum energy functional coupled with the Poisson equation. The relation between the discrete and continuum model is presented below.

E~[C]+Kirchhoff law⇒gradient flow in the discrete model↕↕↕E[c]+Poisson equation⇒ L2 -gradient flow in the continuum model

Let ϕ=diag (ϕ1,ϕ2,…,ϕn) be a diagonal matrix, and ε is arbitrarily small.

Via the expansion p[c+εϕ]=p0+εp1+O(ε2)

dE[c+εϕ]dε∣ε=0=∑k=1d∫Ω(∂xkp0)2ϕk+2ck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)+ν|ck|γ−2ckϕkdx

Multiplicating the Poisson equation with permeability tensor c+εϕ by p0 and integrating by parts, we have

∑k=1d∫Ω(ck+εϕk)(∂xkp0)2+εck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)dx=∫ΩSp0dx+O(ε2)

Thus

O(ε2)=∑k=1d∫Ω(ck+εϕk)(∂xkp0)2+εck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)dx−∫ΩSp0dx=∑k=1d∫Ωεϕk(∂xkp0)2+εck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)dx+[∫Ωck(∂xkp0)2−Sp0dx]=ε∑k=1d∫Ωϕk(∂xkp0)2+ck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)dx

Let ε→0, We obtain the identity

∑k=1d∫Ωϕk(∂xkp0)2+ck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)dx=0

Thus

dE[c+εϕ]dε∣ε=0=∑k=1d∫Ω(∂xkp0)2ϕk+2ck(∂xkp0)(∂xkp1)+ν|ck|γ−2ckϕkdx=∑k=1d∫Ω−(∂xkp0)2ϕk+ν|ck|γ−2ckϕkdx=∑k=1d∫Ω[−(∂xkp0)2+ν|ck|γ−2ck]ϕkdx

Thus we deduce that

∂tck=(∂xkp)2−ν|ck|γ−2ck

In the previous part, we discuss the gradient flow with respect to rectangular parallelotopes. In fact the coordinate transform T:ek→fk leads to the transformed continuum energy functional

E[c]=∫Ω∇pT⋅T[c]⋅∇p+νγ|c|γdx

coupled with the transformed Poisson equation

−∇⋅[T[c]⋅∇p]=S

Here we define the permeability tensor T[c]:=∑k=1dckfk⊗fk.

Thus

∂tck=(fk⋅∇p)2−ν|ck|γ−2ck

Global existence of Solutions of a Modified Macroscopic Model

The establishment of the full PDE system

We notice that the Poisson function suffers from two drawbacks. One is that the diagonal of the tensor c(x) might vanish, while the other one is that the random fluctuations can ill be neglected.

  1. To tackle with the first obstakle we rewirte the permeability tensor with a prescribed function that models the isotropic background permeability of the medium, i.e. T[c]:=rI+c with r(x)≥r0>0, where I is the unit matrix with dimension d. The PDE −∇⋅(T[c]∇p)=S remains elliptic iff diagonal of c(x) are non-negative.

  2. As for the amendment of random fluctuations term, a linear diffusive term is introduced to model the random fluctuations in the medium. Let D2>0 be the constant diffusivity, we thus obtain

    ∂tck=D2∇2ck+∇pT⋅(fk⊗fk)⋅∇p−ν|ck|γ−2ck

Since

D22∇(c+εϕ)T⋅∇(c+εϕ)−D22∇cT⋅∇c=εD2∇cT⋅∇ϕ+O(ε2)

We deduce the amended formal L2-gradient flow of the energy functional

E[c]=∫ΩD22|∇c|2+∇pT⋅T[c]∇p+νγ|c|γdx

Here |∇c|:=∇cT⋅∇c=∑k=1d∂xkck.

The PDE system

∂tck=D2∇2ck+|fk⋅∇p|2−ν|ck|γ−2ckS=−∇⋅(T[c]∇p)T[c]=c+rI

subject to homogeneous Dirichlet boundary boundary conditions for c and no-flux boundary conditions for p. Thus for all x∈∂Ω and t>0

c(t,x)≡0,∂np(t,x)≡0

The initial datum c0(x):=c(0,x) is a diagonal tensor field with non-negative diagonal elements.

Global existence of the weak solutions

The estimation of weak solutions of

∂tck=D2∇2ck+|fk⋅∇p|2−ν|ck|γ−2ckS=−∇⋅(T[c]∇p)T[c]=c+rI

is not supposed to be included in this report. From the research of , we admits a global weak solution (c,p) satisfying

c∈L∞(0,∞;H01(Ω))∩L∞(0,∞;Lγ(Ω))∂tc∈L2((0,∞)×Ω)∇p∈L∞(0,∞;L2(Ω))c∇p∈L∞(0,∞;L2(Ω))

for S∈L2(Ω) and c0(x)∈H01(Ω)d×d∩Lγ(Ω)d×d. While the regularized energy functional satisfied

E′[c(t)]=E′[c0]+∑k=1d∫0t∫Ω(∂tck(s,x))2dxds

for all t∈(0,∞).

 

Acknowledgement

 

 

This report mainly summarise two models of biological transport networks, the discrete (microscopic) one and the cotinuum (macroscopic) one. The analysis of global existence of solutions in the first discrete model (ODE model) provides the theoritical interpretation of optimisation of biological networks. In order to establish the continuous model (PDE model), central difference method is applied. Due to the drawbacks of uncorrected macroscopic model, diffusion and perturbation including random fluctuations are also taken into consideration. The global existence of solutions in the PDE model is mentioned yet not fully illustrated at the final part of the report.

Abstract

Over the seminar in this semester, our group presented a brief introduction to transprot networks based on the research of our instructor Dan Hu, whose theories of adaption and optimisation of Biological Transport Networks is highlighted throughout our presentations.

In pevious presentations, Yang introduced the heuristic discover of networks build by Physarum, drawing forth the research of mathematical model of transport networks. Hereafter, the index of material consumption γ was discussed to characterise the node structure of optimised networks by Tang, where structures of loops were highly underlined. In light of this, Zou analysed how the damage and fluctuations induce loops in optimal transport networks. The systematic theories of modeling is introduced by Ye. Subsequent numerical analysis including solvability of Kirchoff equation, Lagrange conditional extrema, redundancy were individually analysed by Guo. The final presentation of mine was mainly about a macroscopic and continuum model deduced by the previous model in Ye's presentation. The analysis of global existence of solutions was also mentioned.
